* Semi Aquatic Rodents  
* Second Largest Rodent (living)  
  * Up to 110 lbs  
  * Normally 40-70 lbs  
* Two Species (North American and Eurasian)  
* Dams can create wetlands  
* Considered a Keystone Species  
* [Castoreum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castoreum) from castor glands is used in perfume and as a food additive  
  * ***Do more research on castoreum***  
* Live in streams that move slowly, with a gentle incline  
* Aspen, birch, oak, dogwood, willow and alder are some common trees that Beavers eat  
* They sometimes bury wood underwater during the winter as a food source in a cache or “raft”  
* “Beavers can cut down trees up to 15 cm (5.9 in) wide in less than 50 minutes. Thicker trees, at 25 cm (9.8 in) wide or more, may not fall for hours. “  
* There are two types of beaver lodges  
  * An open-water lodge is built in the water over a platform of floating sticks. It is accessed from under the water, and it has a hole in the top for air  
  * A bank lodge is built on the bank of a river/pond, (seen below)  
* Beavers sometimes build canals to help them move along

Effect on the environment

* In creating dams, they created wetland areas which wildly affects the ecosystem around them  
* Help prevent the loss of soil by removing sediments and pollutants from the soil  
* Beavers contribute to climate change (lmao) by causing permafrost to thaw in some areas  
* Beaver engineering can lead to more plant diversity in the area  
* Beavers are invasive in South America, and the trees there cannot regrow after being cut down.  
  * Were introduced to Tierra del Fuego specifically

Communication

* Whines are how adult beavers communicate  
* Kits use mews, squeaks and cries  
* Hissing and Gnashing teeth are defensive behaviors  
* Tail slaps are used to alert threats

* Beavers are mainly nocturnal

## The Beaver: Its Life and Impact, Second Edition

The Eurasian beaver appears more ancient and conservative than its New World cousin, thought to be a younger and more progressive species. (pg 16 in pdf)

Good diagram on pg 18

Extinct Castoroides (Giant Beavers) were thought to be the size of bears, and are still represented as such, but have been evaluated to be closer to 60kg to 100kg. (pg 19-20)

Height and Weight is explained on pg 23

They have a third eyelid to protect their eyes underwater pg 23

Their enamel on their incisors is orange pg25, they have 20 teeth total 

The second toe of each hind foot has a split nail. It serves as a “comb” for preening the fur to keep it fluffy (Fig. 2.2) (pg 25\)

The fur is extremely dense: with 12,000–23,000 hairs/cm2, the beaver has more hair per area of skin than the nutria from warmer zones (8,000–13,000) but less than the river otter (25,000–51,000). (pg 27\)

Beavers have a Cloaca (pg 27\)

Males have a vestigial uterus, the “uterus masculinus,” first described for Eurasian beavers. This structure is also present in North American beavers where in some Canadian populations 100% of the males have it, and in others only 70%. (pg 28\) (I doubt we can really use this information, but I thought it was interesting)

Beavers' eyes, ears and nose can be above the water while swimming, like an alligator. (pg 28\)

The beavers have pretty bad eyesight overall, and can’t see that well underwater. (pg 29\)

The beaver's lips can close behind its incisors, so it can still gnaw underwater. (pg 31\)

Hind legs are webbed, but not the front limbs (pg31)

Normally dive for 5-6 minutes, with a 15 min absolute limit (pg32) \[Could have a part where the main beaver has to dive for way longer than they want, and this gets mentioned\]

**Jumped to CH13 (pg125)**

Beavers are able to live all across the United States and much of canada, even in less than ideal conditions (pg 125-126)

Beavers were instrumental in the biological recovery of Mt. St.Helens. (pg 126\)

Beavers prefer less steep terrain with diverse vegetation around it (pg 127\)

The less steep the stream the better, and wider streams are much preferred to narrow ones (pg 127), though this is less important in areas with high population density. \[Maybe the main beaver gets kicked out to a steeper stream\]

North American beavers largely prefer Aspen trees, and Eurasian beavers prefer Willow trees. (pg 128\)

“In New York State, after aspen and willow, their order of preference ranges from birch, black cherry, beech, juneberry, and hornbeam to maples, hawthorn, and hemlock. The least-preferred species are the conifers such as balsam fir, white pine, Scots pine, red pine, and Norway spruce” (pg 128\)

While moving to a more suitable location, beavers will occupy less suitable places as they move. These are called “Marginal Sites” (pg 129\)

To prevent flooding, some beavers build a small pond off of the main stream, though this has the disadvantages of being more vulnerable to low stream levels. (pg 130\)

**Jump back to CH7 (pg 66\)**

“Thus, to the beaver the pond is highway, canal, lock (in two senses), escape route, hiding place, vegetable garden, food storage facility, refrigerator/freezer, water storage tank, bathtub, swimming pool, and water toilet” (pg 66\)

The height of a dam ranges from 20 cm up to 3 meters tall. (pg 66\)  
The length of a dam ranges wildly from .3m to several hundred meters (pg 66-67)

**The process of building a dam is on pg 67 and should be read**

During droughts and low water flows, beavers will cover the Dam with sediment and mud and raise the dam in order to hog the water. (pg 67-68)

Beaver dams are superior to man-made concrete dams in retaining water and releasing it slowly. (pg 68\)

North American Beavers are the GOAT and better than eurasian beavers (pg 68\)

Beaver Dams have inspired new hydroelectric dam designs, that are more friendly to the environment than traditional dams (pg 68\)

There are 3 types of beaver lodges, *bank holes, bank lodges* and *free-standing lodges.*   
Bank Holes are tunnels in steep slopes, with the entrances underwater.  
Bank Lodges are bank holes that have had sticks piled around the entrance and any holes.  
Free-Standing Lodges are lodges that are fully surrounded by water. (pg 68\)

“The size of a lodge can vary from a tiny, sloppy “trial lodge” of a young first time settler (see Plate 25\) to a massive family fortress that measures 6 m in diameter or more at the water line (and much more at its true base) and over 2 m high.” (pg 69\)

A full lodge can be built in as little as 2 nights. (pg 69\)

While foraging under the ice in the winter, the internal temperature of the beaver can drop below 34 Celsius. (pg 70\)  
![][image2] 

Both North American and Eurasian beavers live in some parts of Russia, but the Eurasian Beaver is less likely to build dams and lodges than the NA beaver. (pg 71\)

When extreme flooding made it difficult to create a new lodge, beavers adapted by building an “upper floor” on their existing lodges. (pg 71\)

Muskrats sometimes pilfer twigs from beaver lodges. (pg 71\)

Deer Mice, Southern Red-Backed Voles and Shrews sometimes gather nesting material from within a beaver lodge. (pg 71\)

**Jump back to pg 32**

In a single inhale-exhale cycle, Beavers can exchange up to 75% of the air in their lungs, compared to humans 15%. (pg 32\)

A beaver’s heart rate drops as it dives. (pg 32\)

This taught us that Humans have a similar thing, where when submerging our face for 30+ seconds in cold water, it lowers our heart rate by 10 \- 40%. (pg 32\)

The beaver tail serves as a heat exchanger, sending warm blood back to the core while the tail itself has colder blood. (pg 33\)

This means the tail can cool them down during the summer, but will not make them more cold during the winter. (pg 34\)

**CH4**

Beavers eat about 1-2kg of wood per day, which is about 1250 to 2500 digestible calories per day. (pg 36\)

From spring to fall, tail volume doubles. As the fat is used up, the dimension of the tail decreases in winter. (pg 38\)

Beavers can swim up to 7 km/hour (4.3 miles/hour). Their mean speed has been measured as 2.3 km/hour (1.4 miles/hour) (pg 39\)

**CH5**

A typical beaver family consists of 2 kits, 2 yearlings and the 2 parents (6 total). Beavers leave the family when they reach about 2 years of age. (pg 41\)

When population density is high, sometimes a 2 year old stays with the family as an additional adult (pg 41\) \[The main beaver () should be 2 years old, and want to stay on as an additional adult but not be allowed\]

Beaver families may use multiple lodges. (pg 42\)

When Beavers are forced to relocate with their kits, they carry them with their forepaws under their chin. (pg 42\)

Beavers will wash the places that they sleep and live. (pg 43\) \[Maybe have a scene where a Mother Beaver is instructing her yearlings to wash the bedding\]

Older beaver offspring (1st-2nd years) will help raise their younger siblings instead of going off on their own immediately. (pg 44\)

Adult beavers normally do not respond when kits slap the water with their tail (pg 45\)

“While the parents dredged up mud from the pond bottom near the dam and added it to the dam, a youngster also dived and picked up mud, but much farther from the dam. Mud in paws, the young beaver swam to the dam, leaving a wake of muddy water. He arrived at the dam empty-handed.” (pg 45\) \[This feels like something that should happen to our beaver\]

## Funny Facts

“In 1760, the College of Physicians and the Faculty of Divinity in Paris permitted beaver meat on fasting days because the beaver’s scaly tail classified it as a fish and not a mammal\!” (14)

“Strange materials end up in beaver dams. In eastern Louisiana, beavers worked paper money stolen from a casino into their dam after three bags of dollar bills had been dumped into a beaver stream, leading to this “money laundering.””(68)
